## **Slide 2: Introduction**
**Problem Statement:**  
- Monte Carlo simulations **fail for P&C** due to **low-frequency, high-severity events**.  
- **MAPE is unstable** for P&C because of extreme loss outliers.
- We explore **Extreme Value Theory (EVT)** as a better alternative.

---

## **Slide 3: Why Monte Carlo Fails for P&C?**
**Monte Carlo Assumptions:**  
âœ… Assumes losses follow a **normal distribution**.  
âœ… Works well when **data is dense & continuous** (e.g., Bank losses).  
ğŸš¨ **Fails for P&C because:**
- P&C losses are **skewed & rare**.
- High variance due to **low event frequency**.
- Extreme outliers cause **unstable MAPE**.

---

## **Slide 4: Alternative Method - Extreme Value Theory (EVT)**
**Why EVT?**  
âœ… **Focuses only on extreme losses** (outliers).  
âœ… **Generalized Pareto Distribution (GPD)** models rare events.  
âœ… Works even if **data is sparse or irregular**.

---

## **Slide 5: EVT Model Implementation**
**Steps:**  
1ï¸âƒ£ Extract top **5% highest losses** as extreme events.
2ï¸âƒ£ Fit a **Generalized Pareto Distribution (GPD)**.  
3ï¸âƒ£ Generate **predicted losses** using EVT.
4ï¸âƒ£ Compare **EVT predictions vs actual losses**.

